 \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1,3-diazinane-2,4-dione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"dihydrouracil\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6N2O2/c7-3-1-2-5-4(8)6-3/h1-2H2,(H2,5,6,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"beta-alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c4-2-1-3(5)6/h1-2,4H2,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C9H13N2O8P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"uridine 2',3'-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"\u03b2-ribouridine-2',3'-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C9H12N2O9P2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"uridine monophosphate derivative\",\n      \"common_name\": \"UMP-like phosphorylated uridine\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_024\",\n      \"formula\": \"C9H12N2O6\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1-beta-D-ribofuranosylpyrimidine-2,4(1H,3H)-dione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"uridine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C9H12N2O6/c12-3-1-5(16)8(17-4-3)11-7(14)2-6(13)10-9(11)15/h2-5,8,12,16H,1,4H2,(H,10,13,15)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_025\",\n      \"formula\": \"[(uridylyl)n]\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"polyuridylate-like oligoribonucleotide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"poly(U)-like oligomer\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_026\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,4-dioxo-1,2,3,4-tetrahydropyrimidine-6-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"orotic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H4N2O4/c8-3-1-2(5(10)11)6-4(9)7-3/h1H,(H,10,11)(H2,6,7,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_027\",\n      \"formula\": \"extraterrestrial mixture\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"meteoritic organic input\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Ryugu-like organics\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent, H2-rich, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to formate on iron-sulfur phases under alkaline hydrothermal conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction on Fe-S minerals is a core vent process and provides reduced C1 feedstock needed for downstream prebiotic organics; this is consistent with iron-sulfur vent chemistry summarized in Huber & Wachtershauser (1997) and Cody et al. (2000), and with alkaline vent concentration concepts in Herschy et al. (2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor or vent-wall reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-mediated CO/CO2 hydrogenation and carbon-carbon coupling produce oxygenated aldehydes including formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal FTT-like reactions on magnetite/iron provide plausible aldehyde precursors that feed the formose and aminooxazole chemistry required for pyrimidine networks; use here is literature-grounded as a connecting step based on hydrothermal carbon fixation frameworks from Cody et al. (2000), Huber & Wachtershauser (1997), and Herschy et al. (2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanide generation and concentration from reduced atmospheric/hydrothermal feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed evaporitic or geothermal surface settings with redox-active nitrogen chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical and redox processes convert reduced C1 species into cyanide-family products that accumulate during drying/freezing cycles.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep literature emphasizes HCN as the central feedstock but leaves geological-scale concentration unresolved; this connecting step is explicitly speculative yet necessary to connect hydrothermal reduced carbon to the experimentally demonstrated HCN-based uracil network. It is justified by the concentration problem discussion and the importance of transient reducing episodes in Sanchez et al. (1966), Miyakawa et al. (2002), Green et al. (2022), and Ferus et al. (2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN hydrolysis to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surfaces aiding concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporation and fumarolic concentration; thermophoretic enrichment in pores over 45-90 days\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolytic conversion of cyanide-derived species yields formamide, which accumulates by evaporation owing to its high boiling point.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is specifically described as the hydrolysis product of HCN and a key uracil-forming solvent/reagent; concentration in volcanic or porous systems is supported by Niether et al. (2016) and reviewed in Saladino et al. (2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN tetramerization to DAMN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"concentrating mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"0.1-1.0 M HCN, pH ~9\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN oligomerizes under alkaline concentrated conditions to the tetramer diaminomaleonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"DAMN is identified in the literature review as a major branch point formed readily from 0.1-1.0 M HCN near pH 9; this follows Ferris and Orgel-era HCN oligomerization chemistry as summarized in Hill & Orgel (2002) and Bizzarri et al. (2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-derived production of cyanoacetylene\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"photochemical mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"spark-discharge or high-energy atmospheric processing reflected in depositional surface capture\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy cyanide chemistry generates cyanoacetylene, which is then trapped in surface waters and lagoons.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanoacetylene is a dominant uracil precursor family member and is reported at up to 8.4% relative to HCN in discharge experiments; this node follows Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966) and supports multiple downstream pyrimidine routes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene hydrolysis to cyanoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pools or warm ponds\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aqueous transformation of cyanoacetylene affords the much more stable cyanoacetaldehyde reservoir species.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature explicitly identifies cyanoacetaldehyde as the hydrolysis product of cyanoacetylene and ~1000 times more stable in water, making it central to the Robertson-Miller route; supported by Robertson & Miller (1995) and Nelson et al. (2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN hydrolysis/oxidation to cyanate and urea-rich pool chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate-buffered evaporitic concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"dry-down in lagoons or frozen/reducing urea systems\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide-derived nitrogen species partition into cyanate and urea pools during hydrolysis, oxidation, and concentration cycles.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanate and especially concentrated urea are required for the Ferris-Sanchez-Orgel and Robertson-Miller pyrimidine routes; cyanate instability and evaporitic urea concentration are specifically highlighted in Ferris et al. (1968), Robertson & Miller (1995), and Menor-Salv\u00e1n et al. (2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolaldehyde plus cyanamide to 2-aminooxazole\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"near-neutral pH, phosphate-buffered solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Phosphate-catalyzed condensation of glycolaldehyde with cyanamide produces the aminooxazole heterocycle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the gateway step of the Powner-Sutherland pyrimidine nucleotide pathway; 2-aminooxazole formation from glycolaldehyde and cyanamide with phosphate catalysis is established by Powner et al. (2009) and discussed in Todd et al. (2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"2-Aminooxazole plus glyceraldehyde to pentose aminooxazoline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate buffer and borate stabilization\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH ~7, ribose aminooxazoline enrichment by crystallization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbonyl addition/cyclization converts aminooxazole and glyceraldehyde into pentose aminooxazolines, including ribose aminooxazoline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step follows directly from the Powner\u2013Gerland\u2013Sutherland pathway and the reported predominance of ribose aminooxazoline at pH 7 in phosphate buffer; supported by Powner et al. (2009) and Ricardo et al. (2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene route to cytosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"0.025 M cyanoacetylene + 0.05 M cyanate, 24 h\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetylene adds cyanate to form cyanovinylurea intermediates that cyclize to cytosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the classic Ferris-Sanchez-Orgel route to cytosine, reported at ~6-19% yield at 100\u00b0C over 24 h; uracil then arises by hydrolytic deamination of cytosine. Supported by Ferris, Sanchez & Orgel (1968).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde plus concentrated urea to cytosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"drying mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporating lagoon; saturated urea gives 30-50% cytosine, dry-down from dilute solution yields 0.23% cytosine and 0.08% uracil\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of cyanoacetaldehyde with concentrated urea forms cytosine efficiently; under dry-down some uracil also appears directly via hydrolysis/deamination.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the highest-yield free-pyrimidine prebiotic route described in the literature. Supported by Robertson & Miller (1995); storage-form dimer reactivity is supported by Nelson et al. (2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolytic deamination of cytosine to uracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"273-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"slow at low temperature, faster at 100C; no O2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Water-mediated deamination replaces the exocyclic amino group of cytosine with oxo, yielding uracil.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cytosine deamination to uracil is a central, unavoidable kinetic link in uracil chemistry and explains uracil detection without cytosine in meteorites. Half-life data and thermodynamic instability of cytosine are documented by Levy & Miller (1998), Wolfenden et al. (2016), and discussed by Shapiro (1999).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide thermolysis on montmorillonite to uracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"413-433K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"formamide-rich drying or fumarolic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Heated formamide condenses on mineral surfaces through multistep radical and ionic pathways to pyrimidinones including uracil.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Saladino and co-workers demonstrated uracil production from heated formamide with mineral catalysts, including montmorillonite; catalyst identity strongly affects product distribution. Supported by Saladino et al. (2004) and Saladino et al. (2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide photothermal chemistry on TiO2 to uracil-family pyrimidines\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"413-433K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"UV wavelengths <380 nm; volcanic ash/fumarolic setting; formaldehyde-enhanced photocatalysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-activated TiO2 generates reactive carbonyl and radical species from formamide and formaldehyde, enabling pyrimidine formation including uracil derivatives.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"TiO2 is uniquely important in formamide chemistry because photocatalytic formaldehyde generation changes pyrimidine product distributions; while thymine and 5-hydroxymethyluracil are especially emphasized, uracil is part of the broader formamide nucleobase suite. Supported by Saladino et al. (2003), Senanayake & Idriss (2006), and Saladino et al. (2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Impact/plasma formamide chemistry to uracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_027\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_024\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"273K to plasma-local high energy\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"powdered meteoritic/mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"laser-induced plasma or proton irradiation of formamide with meteorite powders\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy dissociation of formamide generates CN\u00b7 and NH\u00b7 radicals that recombine into nucleobases; in meteorite-assisted irradiations, nucleosides including uridine also appear.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This route is directly supported by high-energy formamide experiments producing all canonical RNA nucleobases and, in meteorite-assisted irradiations, uridine itself. Supported by Ferus et al. (2015) and Saladino et al. (2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Photothermal HCN polymer chemistry from DAMN to pyrimidines including uracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-active mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"photothermal regime; selectivity shifts toward pyrimidines under irradiation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Energy-dependent rearrangement and multicomponent HCN oligomer chemistry channels DAMN toward pyrimidine products rather than imidazoles.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep report identifies DAMN as a major branch point and notes that under photothermal conditions it participates in multicomponent reactions yielding pyrimidine derivatives, with photochemical conditions favoring pyrimidines. Supported by Bizzarri et al. (2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal cyanide polymerization to uracil and orotic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_026\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"iron-sulfur mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"simulated alkaline hydrothermal/subaerial vent conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Concentrated cyanide polymerizes under mild alkaline hydrothermal conditions to a product distribution enriched in pyrimidines, including uracil and orotic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A 2022 Scientific Reports study showed cyanide polymerization under simulated alkaline hydrothermal conditions preferentially generates pyrimidines including uracil and orotic acid. This route specifically links hydrothermal settings directly to the target. Supported by Bizzarri et al. (2022) as summarized in the deep report.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Beta-alanine plus urea dry-down to dihydrouracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"mild heating\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporation and drying in warm little pond conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation and ring closure during evaporation convert beta-alanine and urea into the reduced pyrimidine dihydrouracil.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows the Chittenden-Schwartz warm-pool pathway in which evaporation and mild heating with clay minerals yield dihydrouracil prior to UV oxidation to uracil. Supported by Chittenden & Schwartz (1976) and Schwartz & Chittenden (1977).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"UV conversion of dihydrouracil to uracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-exposed mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"strong prebiotic UV irradiation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical dehydrogenation/aromatization converts dihydrouracil into uracil.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep report explicitly identifies UV conversion of dihydrouracil to uracil in the Chittenden-Schwartz pathway. Supported by Chittenden & Schwartz (1976) and Schwartz & Chittenden (1977).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Powner-Sutherland assembly of uridine cyclic phosphate bypassing free uracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient with UV step\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"phosphate participates throughout; 254 nm irradiation drives photoanomerization and partial C->U deamination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pentose aminooxazoline reacts with cyanoacetylene to anhydronucleoside intermediates, which upon phosphorylation and UV processing yield beta-ribouridine-2',3'-cyclic phosphate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the canonical Powner-Gerland-Sutherland bypass route that solves the glycosylation problem by building sugar and base together rather than forming free uracil first. Supported by Powner et al. (2009), Xu et al. (2017), and Hud et al. (2016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis or cleavage of uridine cyclic phosphate to uracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_024\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient to mild heating\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool or membrane-associated hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial hydrolysis of nucleotide/nucleoside pools liberates uridine and free uracil through glycosidic bond cleavage and base release.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep report emphasizes that the Powner route yields uridine-type nucleotides rather than free uracil; this cleavage step is added conservatively to connect that literature-supported branch to the target and is therefore somewhat speculative but chemically necessary for a unified target-centered network. It is justified by the known instability and hydrolytic interconversion of nucleosides/nucleotides discussed in Hud et al. (2016), Kim & Benner (2019), and Ross & Deamer (2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_023\",\n      \"name\": \"Uridine phosphorylation to UMP-like species\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_024\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"333-353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"schreibersite 60-80C or diamidophosphate paste conditions over days\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Prebiotic phosphorylating agents convert uridine into mono- or cyclic phosphate derivatives.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The phosphorylation problem is strongly constrained by literature: schreibersite phosphorylates uridine at 60-80C, and diamidophosphate converts uridine efficiently to cyclic UMP-type products. Supported by Gull et al. (2015), Gibard et al. (2018), and Walton et al. (2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_024\",\n      \"name\": \"Montmorillonite-assisted oligomerization of uridine phosphates\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_025\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient to wet-dry cycling\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"clay-rich mineral interfaces; activated uridine phosphate analogs oligomerize to 25-30 mers\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Template-free mineral-assisted condensation of uridine phosphate derivatives yields poly(U)-like oligomers.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Although the reaction occurs on montmorillonite, this node is placed in the biochemical stage to represent assembly at mineral interfaces after nucleotide formation. Ferris reported montmorillonite-catalyzed oligomerization of activated uridine nucleotides to 25-30 mers. Supported by Ferris (2002).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Ferris-Sanchez-Orgel cyanoacetylene-cyanate route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is converted to cyanoacetylene and cyanate; cyanoacetylene reacts with cyanate to form cytosine, which hydrolyzes to uracil.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Robertson-Miller evaporating lagoon route\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanoacetylene hydrolyzes to cyanoacetaldehyde, which condenses with concentrated urea during dry-down to give cytosine and some uracil directly; cytosine further deaminates to uracil.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct dry-down uracil from cyanoacetaldehyde and urea\",\n      \"description\": \"The Robertson-Miller system yields a small amount of uracil directly during evaporative heating without requiring separate isolation of cytosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-montmorillonite thermolysis route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN hydrolyzes to formamide, which upon heating on montmorillonite in fumarolic or drying settings yields uracil.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"TiO2-assisted photothermal formamide route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde feeds surface formamide/TiO2 photochemistry, leading to uracil-family pyrimidines under UV irradiation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Impact-plasma formamide synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"Formamide exposed to plasma or proton irradiation in the presence of meteoritic minerals yields uracil directly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"DAMN photothermal pyrimidine branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Concentrated HCN oligomerizes to DAMN, which under photothermal conditions gives pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal cyanide polymerization route\",\n      \"description\": \"Under simulated alkaline hydrothermal conditions, cyanide polymerization on iron-sulfur minerals yields uracil directly together with orotic acid.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Beta-alanine urea dihydrouracil route\",\n      \"description\": \"Evaporative surface chemistry converts beta-alanine and urea to dihydrouracil on clay minerals, followed by UV conversion to uracil.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Powner-Sutherland nucleotide bypass to released uracil\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal glycolaldehyde feeds aminooxazole chemistry; pentose aminooxazoline reacts with cyanoacetylene and phosphate/UV processing to give uridine cyclic phosphate, from which uracil can be released by hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_021\", \"rxn_022\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_022\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_009\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_021\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Uracil", "overall_strategy": "This network models uracil as a systems-level product emerging from interconnected hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon feedstocks and HCN-related precursors; surface environments concentrate and photochemically transform these into cytosine, dihydrouracil, free uracil, or uridine precursors; biochemical/prebiotic settings convert surface-generated intermediates into uridine/UMP-like species and RNA oligomers. The design follows literature-supported uracil routes centered on the cyanoacetylene/cyanoacetaldehyde family, cytosine hydrolysis, formamide chemistry, HCN polymerization via DAMN, \u03b2-alanine + urea condensation, and the Powner\u2013Sutherland pyrimidine nucleotide bypass, while also representing extraterrestrial delivery as an input node integrated into terrestrial chemistry.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanenitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h2,4H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "carbamide", "common_name": "urea", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3HN", "iupac_name": "prop-2-ynenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3HN/c1-2-3-4/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H3NO", "iupac_name": "3-oxopropanenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h1,3H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "CHNO", "iupac_name": "cyanic acid", "common_name": "cyanate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHNO/c2-1-3/h(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H4N4", "iupac_name": "2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile", "common_name": "DAMN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h7-8H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "CH2N2", "iupac_name": "cyanamide", "common_name": "cyanamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C2H4N2O", "iupac_name": "1,3-oxazol-2-amine, 4,5-dihydro-", "common_name": "2-aminooxazole", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4N2O/c3-2-4-1-5-2/h1H2,(H2,3,4)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H8N2O2", "iupac_name": "pentose aminooxazoline", "common_name": "ribose aminooxazoline", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H5N3O", "iupac_name": "4-aminopyrimidin-2(1H)-one", "common_name": "cytosine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H5N3O/c5-3-1-2-6-4(8)7-3/h1-2H,(H3,5,6,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C4H4N2O2", "iupac_name": "pyrimidine-2,4(1H,3H)-dione", "common_name": "uracil", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N2O2/c7-3-1-2-5-4(8)6-3/h1-2H,(H2,5,6,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C4H6N2O2", "iupac_name": "1,3-diazinane-2,4-dione", "common_name": "dihydrouracil", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6N2O2/c7-3-1-2-5-4(8)6-3/h1-2H2,(H2,5,6,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "3-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "beta-alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c4-2-1-3(5)6/h1-2,4H2,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C9H13N2O8P", "iupac_name": "uridine 2',3'-cyclic phosphate", "common_name": "\u03b2-ribouridine-2',3'-cyclic phosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "C9H12N2O9P2", "iupac_name": "uridine monophosphate derivative", "common_name": "UMP-like phosphorylated uridine", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_024", "formula": "C9H12N2O6", "iupac_name": "1-beta-D-ribofuranosylpyrimidine-2,4(1H,3H)-dione", "common_name": "uridine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C9H12N2O6/c12-3-1-5(16)8(17-4-3)11-7(14)2-6(13)10-9(11)15/h2-5,8,12,16H,1,4H2,(H,10,13,15)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_025", "formula": "[(uridylyl)n]", "iupac_name": "polyuridylate-like oligoribonucleotide", "common_name": "poly(U)-like oligomer", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_026", "formula": "C4H4N2O3", "iupac_name": "2,4-dioxo-1,2,3,4-tetrahydropyrimidine-6-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "orotic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H4N2O4/c8-3-1-2(5(10)11)6-4(9)7-3/h1H,(H,10,11)(H2,6,7,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_027", "formula": "extraterrestrial mixture", "iupac_name": "meteoritic organic input", "common_name": "Ryugu-like organics", "inchi": null, "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent, H2-rich, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to formate on iron-sulfur phases under alkaline hydrothermal conditions.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction on Fe-S minerals is a core vent process and provides reduced C1 feedstock needed for downstream prebiotic organics; this is consistent with iron-sulfur vent chemistry summarized in Huber & Wachtershauser (1997) and Cody et al. (2000), and with alkaline vent concentration concepts in Herschy et al. (2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor or vent-wall reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Surface-mediated CO/CO2 hydrogenation and carbon-carbon coupling produce oxygenated aldehydes including formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal FTT-like reactions on magnetite/iron provide plausible aldehyde precursors that feed the formose and aminooxazole chemistry required for pyrimidine networks; use here is literature-grounded as a connecting step based on hydrothermal carbon fixation frameworks from Cody et al. (2000), Huber & Wachtershauser (1997), and Herschy et al. (2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface cyanide generation and concentration from reduced atmospheric/hydrothermal feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed evaporitic or geothermal surface settings with redox-active nitrogen chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical and redox processes convert reduced C1 species into cyanide-family products that accumulate during drying/freezing cycles.", "reasoning": "The deep literature emphasizes HCN as the central feedstock but leaves geological-scale concentration unresolved; this connecting step is explicitly speculative yet necessary to connect hydrothermal reduced carbon to the experimentally demonstrated HCN-based uracil network. It is justified by the concentration problem discussion and the importance of transient reducing episodes in Sanchez et al. (1966), Miyakawa et al. (2002), Green et al. (2022), and Ferus et al. (2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "HCN hydrolysis to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surfaces aiding concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporation and fumarolic concentration; thermophoretic enrichment in pores over 45-90 days"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolytic conversion of cyanide-derived species yields formamide, which accumulates by evaporation owing to its high boiling point.", "reasoning": "Formamide is specifically described as the hydrolysis product of HCN and a key uracil-forming solvent/reagent; concentration in volcanic or porous systems is supported by Niether et al. (2016) and reviewed in Saladino et al. (2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "HCN tetramerization to DAMN", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "concentrating mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "0.1-1.0 M HCN, pH ~9"}, "mechanism": "HCN oligomerizes under alkaline concentrated conditions to the tetramer diaminomaleonitrile.", "reasoning": "DAMN is identified in the literature review as a major branch point formed readily from 0.1-1.0 M HCN near pH 9; this follows Ferris and Orgel-era HCN oligomerization chemistry as summarized in Hill & Orgel (2002) and Bizzarri et al. (2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "HCN-derived production of cyanoacetylene", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "photochemical mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "spark-discharge or high-energy atmospheric processing reflected in depositional surface capture"}, "mechanism": "High-energy cyanide chemistry generates cyanoacetylene, which is then trapped in surface waters and lagoons.", "reasoning": "Cyanoacetylene is a dominant uracil precursor family member and is reported at up to 8.4% relative to HCN in discharge experiments; this node follows Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966) and supports multiple downstream pyrimidine routes."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cyanoacetylene hydrolysis to cyanoacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pools or warm ponds"}, "mechanism": "Aqueous transformation of cyanoacetylene affords the much more stable cyanoacetaldehyde reservoir species.", "reasoning": "The literature explicitly identifies cyanoacetaldehyde as the hydrolysis product of cyanoacetylene and ~1000 times more stable in water, making it central to the Robertson-Miller route; supported by Robertson & Miller (1995) and Nelson et al. (2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "HCN hydrolysis/oxidation to cyanate and urea-rich pool chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate-buffered evaporitic concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "dry-down in lagoons or frozen/reducing urea systems"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide-derived nitrogen species partition into cyanate and urea pools during hydrolysis, oxidation, and concentration cycles.", "reasoning": "Cyanate and especially concentrated urea are required for the Ferris-Sanchez-Orgel and Robertson-Miller pyrimidine routes; cyanate instability and evaporitic urea concentration are specifically highlighted in Ferris et al. (1968), Robertson & Miller (1995), and Menor-Salv\u00e1n et al. (2009)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Glycolaldehyde plus cyanamide to 2-aminooxazole", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate", "aqueous": "true", "other": "near-neutral pH, phosphate-buffered solution"}, "mechanism": "Phosphate-catalyzed condensation of glycolaldehyde with cyanamide produces the aminooxazole heterocycle.", "reasoning": "This is the gateway step of the Powner-Sutherland pyrimidine nucleotide pathway; 2-aminooxazole formation from glycolaldehyde and cyanamide with phosphate catalysis is established by Powner et al. (2009) and discussed in Todd et al. (2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "2-Aminooxazole plus glyceraldehyde to pentose aminooxazoline", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate buffer and borate stabilization", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH ~7, ribose aminooxazoline enrichment by crystallization"}, "mechanism": "Carbonyl addition/cyclization converts aminooxazole and glyceraldehyde into pentose aminooxazolines, including ribose aminooxazoline.", "reasoning": "This step follows directly from the Powner\u2013Gerland\u2013Sutherland pathway and the reported predominance of ribose aminooxazoline at pH 7 in phosphate buffer; supported by Powner et al. (2009) and Ricardo et al. (2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Cyanoacetylene route to cytosine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "0.025 M cyanoacetylene + 0.05 M cyanate, 24 h"}, "mechanism": "Cyanoacetylene adds cyanate to form cyanovinylurea intermediates that cyclize to cytosine.", "reasoning": "This is the classic Ferris-Sanchez-Orgel route to cytosine, reported at ~6-19% yield at 100\u00b0C over 24 h; uracil then arises by hydrolytic deamination of cytosine. Supported by Ferris, Sanchez & Orgel (1968)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Cyanoacetaldehyde plus concentrated urea to cytosine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_018", "mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "drying mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporating lagoon; saturated urea gives 30-50% cytosine, dry-down from dilute solution yields 0.23% cytosine and 0.08% uracil"}, "mechanism": "Condensation of cyanoacetaldehyde with concentrated urea forms cytosine efficiently; under dry-down some uracil also appears directly via hydrolysis/deamination.", "reasoning": "This is the highest-yield free-pyrimidine prebiotic route described in the literature. Supported by Robertson & Miller (1995); storage-form dimer reactivity is supported by Nelson et al. (2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrolytic deamination of cytosine to uracil", "inputs": ["mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "273-373K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "slow at low temperature, faster at 100C; no O2"}, "mechanism": "Water-mediated deamination replaces the exocyclic amino group of cytosine with oxo, yielding uracil.", "reasoning": "Cytosine deamination to uracil is a central, unavoidable kinetic link in uracil chemistry and explains uracil detection without cytosine in meteorites. Half-life data and thermodynamic instability of cytosine are documented by Levy & Miller (1998), Wolfenden et al. (2016), and discussed by Shapiro (1999)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Formamide thermolysis on montmorillonite to uracil", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "413-433K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "false", "other": "formamide-rich drying or fumarolic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Heated formamide condenses on mineral surfaces through multistep radical and ionic pathways to pyrimidinones including uracil.", "reasoning": "Saladino and co-workers demonstrated uracil production from heated formamide with mineral catalysts, including montmorillonite; catalyst identity strongly affects product distribution. Supported by Saladino et al. (2004) and Saladino et al. (2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Formamide photothermal chemistry on TiO2 to uracil-family pyrimidines", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "413-433K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "false", "other": "UV wavelengths <380 nm; volcanic ash/fumarolic setting; formaldehyde-enhanced photocatalysis"}, "mechanism": "UV-activated TiO2 generates reactive carbonyl and radical species from formamide and formaldehyde, enabling pyrimidine formation including uracil derivatives.", "reasoning": "TiO2 is uniquely important in formamide chemistry because photocatalytic formaldehyde generation changes pyrimidine product distributions; while thymine and 5-hydroxymethyluracil are especially emphasized, uracil is part of the broader formamide nucleobase suite. Supported by Saladino et al. (2003), Senanayake & Idriss (2006), and Saladino et al. (2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Impact/plasma formamide chemistry to uracil", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_027"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_024"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "273K to plasma-local high energy", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "powdered meteoritic/mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "laser-induced plasma or proton irradiation of formamide with meteorite powders"}, "mechanism": "High-energy dissociation of formamide generates CN\u00b7 and NH\u00b7 radicals that recombine into nucleobases; in meteorite-assisted irradiations, nucleosides including uridine also appear.", "reasoning": "This route is directly supported by high-energy formamide experiments producing all canonical RNA nucleobases and, in meteorite-assisted irradiations, uridine itself. Supported by Ferus et al. (2015) and Saladino et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Photothermal HCN polymer chemistry from DAMN to pyrimidines including uracil", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-active mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "photothermal regime; selectivity shifts toward pyrimidines under irradiation"}, "mechanism": "Energy-dependent rearrangement and multicomponent HCN oligomer chemistry channels DAMN toward pyrimidine products rather than imidazoles.", "reasoning": "The deep report identifies DAMN as a major branch point and notes that under photothermal conditions it participates in multicomponent reactions yielding pyrimidine derivatives, with photochemical conditions favoring pyrimidines. Supported by Bizzarri et al. (2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Alkaline hydrothermal cyanide polymerization to uracil and orotic acid", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_026"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "353K", "pressure": "1 bar", "catalyst": "iron-sulfur mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "simulated alkaline hydrothermal/subaerial vent conditions"}, "mechanism": "Concentrated cyanide polymerizes under mild alkaline hydrothermal conditions to a product distribution enriched in pyrimidines, including uracil and orotic acid.", "reasoning": "A 2022 Scientific Reports study showed cyanide polymerization under simulated alkaline hydrothermal conditions preferentially generates pyrimidines including uracil and orotic acid. This route specifically links hydrothermal settings directly to the target. Supported by Bizzarri et al. (2022) as summarized in the deep report."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Beta-alanine plus urea dry-down to dihydrouracil", "inputs": ["mol_021", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "mild heating", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "evaporation and drying in warm little pond conditions"}, "mechanism": "Condensation and ring closure during evaporation convert beta-alanine and urea into the reduced pyrimidine dihydrouracil.", "reasoning": "This follows the Chittenden-Schwartz warm-pool pathway in which evaporation and mild heating with clay minerals yield dihydrouracil prior to UV oxidation to uracil. Supported by Chittenden & Schwartz (1976) and Schwartz & Chittenden (1977)."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "UV conversion of dihydrouracil to uracil", "inputs": ["mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-exposed mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "strong prebiotic UV irradiation"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical dehydrogenation/aromatization converts dihydrouracil into uracil.", "reasoning": "The deep report explicitly identifies UV conversion of dihydrouracil to uracil in the Chittenden-Schwartz pathway. Supported by Chittenden & Schwartz (1976) and Schwartz & Chittenden (1977)."}, {"id": "rxn_021", "name": "Powner-Sutherland assembly of uridine cyclic phosphate bypassing free uracil", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient with UV step", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "phosphate participates throughout; 254 nm irradiation drives photoanomerization and partial C->U deamination"}, "mechanism": "Pentose aminooxazoline reacts with cyanoacetylene to anhydronucleoside intermediates, which upon phosphorylation and UV processing yield beta-ribouridine-2',3'-cyclic phosphate.", "reasoning": "This is the canonical Powner-Gerland-Sutherland bypass route that solves the glycosylation problem by building sugar and base together rather than forming free uracil first. Supported by Powner et al. (2009), Xu et al. (2017), and Hud et al. (2016)."}, {"id": "rxn_022", "name": "Hydrolysis or cleavage of uridine cyclic phosphate to uracil", "inputs": ["mol_022"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_024"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient to mild heating", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "prebiotic pool or membrane-associated hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Partial hydrolysis of nucleotide/nucleoside pools liberates uridine and free uracil through glycosidic bond cleavage and base release.", "reasoning": "The deep report emphasizes that the Powner route yields uridine-type nucleotides rather than free uracil; this cleavage step is added conservatively to connect that literature-supported branch to the target and is therefore somewhat speculative but chemically necessary for a unified target-centered network. It is justified by the known instability and hydrolytic interconversion of nucleosides/nucleotides discussed in Hud et al. (2016), Kim & Benner (2019), and Ross & Deamer (2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_023", "name": "Uridine phosphorylation to UMP-like species", "inputs": ["mol_024"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "333-353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "schreibersite 60-80C or diamidophosphate paste conditions over days"}, "mechanism": "Prebiotic phosphorylating agents convert