thway as a nucleotide pathway rather than forcing it into free uracil production.\",\n        \"Replace rxn_022 with UV-driven photoanomerization/deamination to beta-ribouridine-2,3-cyclic phosphate consistent with Powner-Sutherland.\",\n        \"Use activated uridine phosphates for montmorillonite oligomerization; plain UMP-like species are less supported than activated phosphorimidazolides or dehydrating wet-dry contexts.\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.76,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is ambitious, well connected, and captures many of the major uracil-related motifs from the literature: cyanoacetylene/cyanoacetaldehyde chemistry, cytosine hydrolysis, formamide routes, DAMN branching, beta-alanine plus urea, extraterrestrial delivery, and the Powner-Sutherland bypass. Topologically it is strong, with multiple hubs and convergence points. Environmental interconnection is also broadly successful, showing hydrothermal feedstocks feeding surface chemistry and downstream biochemical assembly.\\n\\nHowever, several chemistry and literature-alignment issues prevent approval at the network level. The biggest recurring problem is overly schematic upstream generation of HCN and cyanoacetylene from hydrothermal feedstocks; this is much less secure than the downstream uracil-forming chemistry and is not represented with the specificity found in the literature. A second issue is environmental labeling: some steps called hydrothermal are really moderate alkaline/subaerial cyanide polymerization settings, while some 'biochemical' steps are simply aqueous hydrolysis or prebiotic photochemistry. Third, the Powner-Sutherland branch is partially misconstrued by forcing release of free uracil, contrary to the literature's key point that the pathway bypasses free-base glycosylation and directly generates nucleotide-like products. Fourth, at least one important precursor, beta-alanine, appears disconnected from the rest of