face nucleotide-fragment assembly without misrepresenting the route as free-uracil synthesis (Powner et al., 2009; Todd et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "2-Aminooxazole plus glyceraldehyde to pentose aminooxazolines", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate-buffered and borate-modulated", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH ~7 favors ribose aminooxazoline"}, "mechanism": "Carbon-carbon bond formation and cyclization generate pentose aminooxazolines, with phosphate controlling speciation and ribose aminooxazoline favored near neutral pH.", "reasoning": "This step is a core part of the Powner-Sutherland pathway and is important because it builds sugar and base fragments together, addressing the glycosylation problem discussed in the report (Powner et al., 2009; Ricardo et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Cyanoacetylene incorporation and phosphorylation to cytidine cyclic phosphate", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient to mild warming", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate in solution", "aqueous": "true", "other": "through anhydronucleoside intermediates followed by phosphorylation"}, "mechanism": "Pentose aminooxazoline derivatives react with cyanoacetylene to form anhydronucleosides, which phosphate converts into activated cytidine cyclic phosphate.", "reasoning": "This reaction collapses the established later stages of the Powner pathway into one node for network economy while preserving the correct logic: cyanoacetylene is incorporated before activated ribocytidine phosphate formation. It intentionally does not generate free uracil (Powner et al., 2009; Xu et al., 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "UV photoanomerization and partial deamination to uridine cyclic phosphate", "inputs": ["mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient under 254 nm UV", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "photoanomerization with partial C-to-U deamination"}, "mechanism": "Ultraviolet irradiation converts the cytidine cyclic phosphate derivative to the beta-anomer and partially deaminates the base to produce uridine cyclic phosphate.", "reasoning": "The report highlights this exact transformation as the key result of the Powner-Sutherland revolution: activated uridine nucleotides arise without ever requiring free uracil glycosylation. This corrects the prior failed attempt (Powner et al., 2009; Xu et al., 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_021", "name": "Hydrolysis/opening of uridine cyclic phosphate to uridine", "inputs": ["mol_022"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient to mild warming", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "prebiotic pool hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolytic ring opening of activated uridine phosphate gives uridine.", "reasoning": "This connector is not the focal discovery of the Powner pathway but is a necessary downstream hydrolysis step linking activated uridine phosphate to later phosphorylation/polymerization chemistry. It is included as a conservative completion step rather than a novel free-base route; downstream uridine chemistry is supported by phosphorylation/polymerization studies (Gibard et al., 2018; Ferris, 2002)."}, {"id": "rxn_022", "name": "Prebiotic phosphorylation of uridine to UMP", "inputs": ["mol_023"], "outputs": ["mol_024"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "60-80C or paste conditions over days", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "schreibersite or diamidophosphate chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "schreibersite gives low yields; diamidophosphate can give high cyclic phosphate conversion"}, "mechanism": "Phosphorylation of uridine forms monophosphate products suitable for oligomerization.", "reasoning": "The report documents uridine phosphorylation by schreibersite and highly efficient phosphorylation/cyclophosphorylation by diamidophosphate. This establishes a uracil-derived nucleotide branch relevant to biochemical assembly (Gull et al., 2015; Gibard et al., 2018; Casta\u00f1eda et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_023", "name": "Montmorillonite-assisted oligomerization of uridine phosphates", "inputs": ["mol_024"], "outputs": ["mol_025"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient to geothermal cycling", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite interfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "rate of oligomerization exceeds hydrolysis; uridine oligomers up to 25-30 mers reported"}, "mechanism": "Clay-templated condensation/polymerization of activated uridine phosphate monomers forms short oligonucleotides.", "reasoning": "Ferris demonstrated montmorillonite-catalyzed oligomerization of activated uridine nucleotides, and Ross & Deamer extended wet-dry polymerization from uridine monophosphate. This provides the biochemical endpoint connected to uracil chemistry (Ferris, 2002; Ross & Deamer, 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_024", "name": "Extraterrestrial delivery of uracil to surface reservoirs", "inputs": ["mol_027"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface adsorption/concentration on minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "meteoritic deposition into warm ponds or sediments; ppb-scale uracil detected in Ryugu"}, "mechanism": "Delivered extraterrestrial uracil is released from meteoritic material and concentrated in surface reservoirs.", "reasoning": "The report makes clear that extraterrestrial uracil is real and likely contributed to prebiotic inventories. This is a source pathway, not a synthesis step, but it is experimentally grounded and relevant to network completeness (Oba et al., 2023; Koga et al., 2026)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Ferris-Sanchez-Orgel cyanate route", "description": "Cyanoacetylene reacts with cyanate to form a cyanovinylurea intermediate ensemble that cyclizes to cytosine; cytosine then hydrolytically deaminates to uracil.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Robertson-Miller evaporating lagoon route", "description": "Cyanoacetaldehyde generated from cyanoacetylene reacts with concentrated urea during dry-down to yield cytosine efficiently and minor uracil directly; cytosine hydrolysis completes the route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_008"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Robertson-Miller direct minor uracil branch", "description": "The same cyanoacetaldehyde + urea dry-down chemistry yields a small amount of uracil directly without requiring separate cytosine hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_008"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Formamide thermolysis on montmorillonite", "description": "Formamide enriched in fumarolic or evaporative settings is heated on montmorillonite to produce uracil directly.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "TiO2-assisted formamide photochemistry", "description": "Formamide undergoes photocatalytic reaction on TiO2 under UV-active volcanic surface conditions, producing uracil-family products including uracil.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_005"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Energetic formamide impact/plasma route", "description": "High-energy activation of formamide by plasma or proton irradiation produces uracil directly and can also generate uridine-related products.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "DAMN photothermal pyrimidine branch", "description": "Concentrated HCN oligomerizes to DAMN, which under photothermal conditions gives pyrimidine derivatives including uracil and cytosine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Moderate alkaline hydrothermal cyanide polymerization", "description": "Under simulated alkaline hydrothermal/subaerial vent conditions, cyanide polymerization yields uracil directly along with orotic acid.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_026"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Ice eutectic cyanide-urea pathway", "description": "Freeze-concentration of cyanide and urea in eutectic films yields cytosine and uracil, with cytosine also feeding secondary deamination to uracil.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_014", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_008"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Beta-alanine surface-pool route", "description": "Beta-alanine condenses with urea during dry-down to dihydrouracil, which UV irradiation converts to uracil.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_015", "mol_008"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_006"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_012", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_016", "rxn_024"], "outgoing_reactions": []}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_014"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_004", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_008", "incoming_reactio